\begin_layout Subsection
Reconstructing 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v,q\right)$
\end_inset

 maps from NGSIM trajectories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The NGSIM does not directely provide the values 
\begin_inset Formula $v\left(t,x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q\left(t,x\right)$
\end_inset

 in the resolution domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,T\right]\times\left[0,L\right]$
\end_inset

.
 In order to obtain macroscopic quantities out of these microscopic measurements
, one divides the time and space grid 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,T\right]\times\left[0,L\right]$
\end_inset

 into small buckets 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left[i\:\Delta t,\:\left(i+1\right)\:\Delta t\right]\times\left[j\:\Delta x,\:\left(j+1\right)\:\Delta t\right]\right)_{i\in\left\{ 1\ldots n_{t}\right\} ,j\in\left\{ 1\ldots n_{x}\right\} }$
\end_inset

.
 This operation consists in gathering the corresponding data points into
 bins.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $card$
\end_inset

 denote the function that gives the number of elements in a given set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Binning formulae
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The size of each bucket is therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\times\Delta x$
\end_inset

.
 In each bucket, a certain number of traces are available.
 In each bucket, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 are assumed to be constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Binning formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{v}_{i,j}=mean_{trace\in bucket_{i,j}}\left(v\left(trace\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Binning formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One considers a bucket with index 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)$
\end_inset

.
 by definition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{i,j}=\frac{1}{n_{lanes}\:\Delta x\:\Delta t}\int\int_{\left(t,x\right)\in\left[i\:\Delta t,\:\left(i+1\right)\:\Delta t\right]\times\left[j\:\Delta x,\:\left(j+1\right)\:\Delta t\right]}\rho\left(x,t\right)dxdt
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Any given vehicle will repeat its trace every 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1$
\end_inset

 seconds.
 Therefore it is also possible to count the number of traces in a given
 bucket and normalize it by the sampling rate.
 The contribution of a given vehicle to the density of a bucket is proportional
 to the number of traces it has left in the bucket.
 If the speed is assumed to be locally constant, this is proportional to
 the time this vehicle spends in the bucket and consistent with the conservation
 of the total number of vehicles across all buckets.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{\rho}_{i,j}=\frac{1}{n_{lanes}\:\Delta x\:\Delta t\:\mbox{sampling rate}}card\left(\left\{ trace\mid trace\:\in\: bucket\right\} \right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Binning formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $q\left(x,t\right)=\rho\left(x,t\right)v\left(x,t\right)$
\end_inset

 so a first estimator for 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{q}_{i,j}=\widehat{v}_{i,j}\widehat{\rho}_{i,j}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

One can also approximate the flux going through a given bucket 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[i\:\Delta t,\:\left(i+1\right)\:\Delta t\right]\times\left[j\:\Delta x,\:\left(j+1\right)\:\Delta t\right]$
\end_inset

 by the number of cars crossing the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(j+1\right)\Delta x$
\end_inset

 between times 
\begin_inset Formula $i\:\Delta t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(i+1\right)\Delta t$
\end_inset

 normalized by the duration 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

If a given vehicle with identification number 
\begin_inset Formula $id_{0}$
\end_inset

 crosses 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(j+1\right)\Delta x$
\end_inset

 between time 
\begin_inset Formula $i\:\Delta t$
\end_inset

 and time 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(i+1\right)\:\Delta t$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $id_{0}$
\end_inset

 is present in the bucket 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[i\:\Delta t,\:\left(i+1\right)\:\Delta t\right]\times\left[j\:\Delta x,\:\left(j+1\right)\:\Delta t\right]$
\end_inset

 and the bucket 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[i\:\Delta t,\:\left(i+1\right)\:\Delta t\right]\times\left[\left(j+1\right)\:\Delta x,\:\left(j+2\right)\:\Delta t\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $card\left(\left\{ id\left(trace\right)\mid trace\in bucket_{i,j}\right\} \cap\left\{ id\left(trace\right)\mid trace\in bucket_{i,j+1}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 is the number of vehicles that have crossed the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(j+1\right)\Delta x$
\end_inset

 in that interval of time.
 This gives another estimator of the flux based on counting cars in a straightfo
rward way: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{q}_{i,j}^{count}=\frac{1}{n_{lanes}\Delta t}\: card\left(\left\{ id\left(trace\right)\mid trace\in bucket_{i,j}\right\} \cap\left\{ id\left(trace\right)\mid trace\in bucket_{i,j+1}\right\} \right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Choosing the number of bins
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The discretisation grid is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left[i\:\Delta t,\:\left(i+1\right)\:\Delta t\right]\times\left[j\:\Delta x,\:\left(j+1\right)\:\Delta t\right]\mid\left(i,j\right)\in\left\{ 1\ldots N\right\} \times\left\{ 1\ldots N\right\} \right\} $
\end_inset

.
 As the estimation formulae above rely on averaving, having a confortable
 number of points in each bin provides better convergence.
 In that case it is worth mentionning that usual Central Limit theorem based
 reasonning for convergence of such estimates is flawed as several samples
 may correspond to the same vehicule or interacting vehicules, therefore
 violating the independence assumption of the theorem.
 The subject of proving the convergence of the estimates above lies clearly
 beyond the scope of this article and therefore, as a rule of thumb we choose
 a setup that guarantees that most buckets will host more than 
\begin_inset Formula $500$
\end_inset

 traces.
 This is achieved with a 
\begin_inset Formula $80\times80$
\end_inset

 grid where the 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{th}$
\end_inset

 percentile of the number of traces in a given bin is 
\begin_inset Formula $485$
\end_inset

.
 Such a grid also yields a 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{th}$
\end_inset

 percentile of 
\begin_inset Formula $58$
\end_inset

 distinct vehicles per bin.
